//A company is conducting an online sale where each item has a unique price. The pricing team wants to quickly identify whether any two items have a specific price difference (say k rupees).This helps them detect potential pricing errors. You are given a list of item prices and an integer k. Your job is to check whether there exists a pair (a, b) such that:
Return / Print
1.Print "Pair Found" if such a pair exists.
2.Otherwise, print "No Pair".
*Test Case 01 :*
Input: arr = [5, 20, 3, 2, 50, 80] k = 78
Output: Pair Found
*Test Case 02 :*
Input: arr = [10, 30, 40, 50, 60] k = 55
Output: No Pair
*Test Case 03 :*
Input: arr = [5, 5, 5, 5] k = 0
Output: Pair Found
*Test Case 04 :*
Input: arr = [-10, 0, 10, 20, 30] k = 20
Output: Pair Found

import java.util.*;

public class PairWithGivenDifference {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);

        // Input size
        int n = sc.nextInt();

        int[] arr = new int[n];

        // Input array elements
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            arr[i] = sc.nextInt();
        }

        // Input k
        int k = sc.nextInt();

        HashSet<Integer> set = new HashSet<>();
        boolean found = false;

        for (int num : arr) {
            if (set.contains(num + k) || set.contains(num - k)) {
                found = true;
                break;
            }
            set.add(num);
        }

        if (found) {
            System.out.println("Pair Found");
        } else {
            System.out.println("No Pair");
        }

        sc.close();
    }
}
